content:
A joined report can contain data from multiple standard or custom report types. You can add report types if they have relationships with the same object or objects. For example, adding Opportunities and Cases reports together because both relate to Accounts.

A joined report consists of up to five report blocks. Each block allows regular and summary fields, standard and cross-block custom summary formulas, filters, and sorting. Groupings can be applied across all blocks, with up to three groupings allowed. A chart can also be added to a joined report.

The principal report type controls common field names. By default, the first added type is the principal. Common fields are shared by report types or have a lookup relationship to them. These fields can be used for grouping and appear in the Fields pane, identified by an icon in Lightning Experience or in the Common Fields area in Salesforce Classic.

Joined reports use SQL outer join. Each row has a corresponding row in the joined report, even if not all blocks match data.

You can add a report type to a joined report, create a summary formula, and work with blocks to further customize your joined report.
title: Understanding Joined Reports in Salesforce Analytics
